imilar.\n\nWe need to evaluate holistically for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calmness under pressure, decision-making, teamwork/communication, professional development.\n\nLet's list strengths/weaknesses:\n\nA: Anticipate dangerous situations (good safety), see complex connections (cognitive), excellent spatial vision (technical), very good leadership (teamwork). Negatives: unfriendly (crew), eats unhealthily (maybe health concerns for long flights). Also possibly not good at criticism, unorganized (if we accept). Overall strong technical, but interpersonal issues.\n\nB: Very conscientious (reliability), handles stress well (calm under pressure), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (technical). Negatives: pretentious, wrong tone (communication), possibly grumpy/uncooperative (teamwork). Overall good technical and stress, but interpersonal issues.\n\nC: Quick correct decisions (decision-making), difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork), egocentric (teamwork), not willing to further education (professional development), puts concern for others above everything (positive for crew), excellent attention skills (technical). Also positive atmosphere (crew), 100% reliable (reliability). Mixed: strong reliability and decision, but communication issues and lack of development.\n\nD: Responds to unexpected events adequately (calm), concentrates well (cognitive), solves problems extremely well (technical), takes responsibility seriously (reliability), moody (teamwork), loner (crew), possibly arrogant/weak leadership (teamwork). Overall strong problem solving, but interpersonal concerns.\n\nWe need to pick provisional preference. Which candidate balances technical competence and teamwork best? Candidate C seems strong reliability, quick decisions, crew atmosphere, but communication difficulty and egocentric. Candidate B strong technical and stress, but pretentious. Candidate A strong technical and leadership but unfriendly